Tuipulotu stayed hot in Week 15, generating four solos, two sacks, and three tackles for loss. Now fifth in the league with 12 sacks, the Chargers' edge rusher has seven sacks in his last seven games, with at least one sack in five of those seven. Fire Tuli up as a top-15 option for Week 16 despite the neutral-at-best matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Chase Young stayed hot in Week 15, racking up four solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Young is up to six sacks on the season, with a sack in three of his last four games, and five of his last seven. Tap Chase as a top-25 option for a tasty Week 16 matchup against the New York Jets. Make the add wherever possible.

Pearce stayed scorching in Week 15, tallying two solos, one assist, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and two passes defended. Suddenly up to an elite eight sacks in his rookie season, Pearce has registered at least one QB takedown in a stellar six straight contests, a span where he recorded 7.5 of his eight sacks on the year. Fire the exciting rookie edge rusher up as a DL2 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Laiatu Latu showed up in Week 15, tallying three solos, one sack, and three tackles for loss. Now up to 6.5 sacks on the season, Latu mercifully recorded his first full sack since Week 9. Treat Laiatu as a boom-or-bust DL3/flex type for a plus Week 16 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Abdul Carter stepped up in Week 15, stacking five solos, two assists, one sack, three tackles for loss, two forced fumbles, and one fumble recovery. Has just 2.5 sacks on the season, but is riding a two game sack streak heading into a tasty Week 16 matchup against the Minnesota Vikings. Tap him as a DL3/flex option where needed in competitive leagues.

Cameron Heyward showed up in Week 15, racking up three solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. The veteran interior pass rusher is sitting at just 2.5 sacks, but has posted two spike weeks in his last three games. Heyward shows up more in his true plus matchups, making him more of a DL3 option for a neutral-at-best Week 16 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Myles Murphy showed up in Week 15, stacking two solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss.  Murphy has looked improved recently, recording a sack in two of his last five games. The once promising prospect may finally be turning a corner in what has been a disappointing start to his career. Murphy remains a dynasty stash but should not be in lineups for Week 16, regardless of league size.

Kobie Turner was at it again in Week 15, tallying three solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. The impressive defensive tackle is now up to 5.5 sacks with at least one sack in three of his last four games. Tap Turner as a DL2/3 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks on Thursday Night Football.

D.J. Wonnum was excellent in Week 15, reeling off two solos, two assists, two sacks, and one tackle for loss. Wonnum had failed to record a sack all season prior to this, so feel free to ignore him for at least one more week. Look elsewhere for Week 16.

Odafe was excellent in Week 15, piling up four solos, two sacks, and three tackles for loss. Oweh is up to seven sacks on the season, with at least one sack in back-to-back games. Treat Oweh as an elite DL3 option for a neutral-at-best Week 16 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Brandon Graham made an impact in Week 15, racking up two solos, two sacks, and one tackle for loss on 17 percent of the snaps. Graham was signed for the playoff run and is not going to see enough snaps to rely on in fantasy. Feel free to ignore for the veteran for Week 16 against Washington.

Jordyn Brooks stayed elite in Week 15, tallying seven solos, six assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Continue to fire Brooks up as a top-three IDP option, regardless of position.

Roquan Smith was at it again in Week 15, ripping off eight solos and six assists. Roquan has had a couple of down weeks, but remains one of the most consistent IDP options there are. Continue to treat the superstar linebacker as a top-five option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Jack Campbell was excellent in Week 15, tallying 10 solos and four assists. Campbell has been an elite LB1 option all season, and that will not change for Week 16 despite the neutral-at-best on paper matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Devin White was at it again in Week 15, ripping off nine solos, seven assists, and two tackles for loss. White has been back to elite LB1 production over the last two weeks and is more than safe to trust as a top-12 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Carson Schwesinger was excellent in Week 15, tallying four solos and 10 assists. The LB3 in fppg since Week 10, Carson can be counted as an LB1 option for what should be a busy afternoon against the Buffalo Bills.

Tyrel Dodson was excellent in Week 15, racking up eight solos and two assists. The LB5 in fppg on the season, Dodson remains an elite LB1 option for Week 16 despite the neutral on paper matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Nate Landman was excellent in Week 15, tallying six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Landman has been a steady LB1 contributor all season and should continue to be one on Thursday night against the Seattle Seahawks. Start him everywhere.

Ernest Jones was excellent in Week 15, tallying five solos and five assists. Jones has recorded five or more solos and five or more assists in three straight games, making him an easy LB1 play for semifinals week. Treat him as such for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Nick Bolton was at it again in Week 15, racking up five solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Bolton has caught fire for IDP managers, providing LB1 value over his last three contests. Tap the Chiefs' linebacker as a top-15 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Kaden Elliss showed up in Week 15, racking up six solos and one tackle for loss. Elliss has been locked in as a top-15 option for much of the season and should be treated as such for Week 16, thanks to a plus matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Zaire showed up in Week 15, tallying seven solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. After starting the season in disappointing fashion, Franklin has stepped it up and checks in as the LB5 in fppg since Week 10. Fire Zaire up as a top-15 option for Week 16, thanks to both his recent production and a plus matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Nakobe Dean was at it again in Week 15, tallying five solos, three assists, and two tackles for loss. Nakobe has been the LB7 in fppg since Week 10 and should be treated as a top-10 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against Washington.

Germaine Pratt was excellent in Week 15, racking up five solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Pratt has been a top-15 option just joining the Indianapolis Colts and should be treated as one for a tasty Week 16 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Edgerrin Cooper was excellent in Week 15, reeling off seven solos, one assist, two tackles for loss, one fumble recovery, and one pass defended. Cooper was making his way into the LB1 conversation early in the season, but has settled in as an LB3 option. Treat him as such for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

T.J. Edwards showed up in Week 15, reeling off five solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Edwards has struggled to stay healthy this season and hasn't quite been himself when he has been on the field. Tap Edwards as an upside LB2 option where needed.

Al-Shaair was excellent in Week 15, ripping off seven solos and five assists. Azeez has started rolling for the IDP managers, putting together four straight plus outings, with at least four solos and three assists in all four. Start Azeez with confidence as a potential LB2 option for Week 16, thanks to a plus matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Patrick Queen showed up on Monday night, racking up nine solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss. Queen has flashed at times this season for IDP managers, but remains more of a flex than someone you want starting as your LB3 for semifinals week. Treat him as such for a neutral-at-best Week 16 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Henry To'oTo'o showed up in Week 15, tallying four solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. To'oTo' has not been a startable option this season due to the logjam at the position when E.J. Speed and Azeez Al-Shaair are healthy. However, Speed was inactive for Week 15, which helped Henry see 100 percent of the snaps for just the second time all season. Tap To'oTo'o as an LB2/3 if Speed is inactive again.

Christian Rozeboom was back in action in Week 15, posting three solos, three assists, and one sack. Rozeboom had some value during the bye weeks, but is not someone fantasy managers should be looking to start in the playoffs. Tap him as a flex2 in 20+ team leagues, but those in smaller league sizes should look elsewhere completely.

Drue was excellent in Week 15, tallying eight solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Tranquill has put together three LB3 or better level performances in his last five games, putting the veteran linebacker on the flex radar for a tasty Week 16 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Matt Milano went off in Week 15, piling up nine solos, one assist, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Milano stepped up when it mattered the most for the Bills and fantasy managers alike, and becomes an option for the final weeks of the season despite being bench depth at best most of the season. The veteran linebacker stepped up in the heavyweight clash against New England and could be leaned on heavily again this week if Terrel Bernard is sidelined again. Treat him as an LB3/flex option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Demetrius Knight showed up in Week 15, racking up five solos, one assist, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Knight has had some standout performances this season, but this was the highest output of his rookie season. Continue to treat him as an LB3/flex despite the incredible production against Baltimore.

Darius Muasau was excellent in Week 15, racking up five solos and six assists. It was just the second plus outing of the season for Muasau, and we are not sure what the snap split will look like once Demetirus Flanningan-Fowles is healthy, so Muasau should be left on benches wherever possible, even in the deepest of leagues. Look elsewhere for your Week 16 flex/flex2 option.

Jack Gibbens showed up in Week 15, racking up four solos, five assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Gibbens played every snap with Robert Spillane active only as emergency depth and reminded us why fantasy managers had high hopes for him earlier this season. He will get another start if Spillane's foot injury doesn't improve. Start Gibbens as an LB3/flex option if he gets the start.

Greenlaw was productive in Week 15, racking up five solos and three assists. The showing makes it three plus outings in his last five, but Dre has struggled in the solo department prior to this, instead relying on peripheral contributions. Tap him as an upside LB3/flex option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

D'Marco Jackson stepped up in Week 15, reeling off two solos, five assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one interception, and two passes defended. His solo count has been muted since Week 12, but this performance puts Jackson back on the flex radar for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Green Bay Packers. Add and start D'Marco where needed in deeper formats.

Elandon Roberts showed up in Week 15, racking up six solos, three assists, and three tackles for loss. Elandon has had some spike weeks, but has not been productive enough to trust outside of 20+ team leagues. Those in 12-team leagues should look elsewhere for Week 16 despite the strong production and plus matchup.

Denzel Perryman showed up in Week 15, racking up four solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Perryman has been a low floor LB3/4 option since returning from injury and is not someone you should feel comfortable sticking into lineups in the fantasy playoffs unless you play in 20+ team leagues. Avoid Perryman where possible for a neutral on paper matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Austin Booker showed up in Week 15, racking up three solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Booker has been a quality depth piece when he has been active this season and is now up to three sacks in his seven games on the season. With that said, he is not someone those in 12-team leagues should be looking to plug into lineups for Week 16. Look elsewhere.

Mohamoud Diabate showed up in Week 15, racking up four solos, four assists, and two tackles for loss. The Browns linebacker has been a non-factor this season due to playing behind Devin Bush and Carson Schwesinger in nickel packages, but played a season high 52 percent of the snaps against Chicago. The snap increase seems to be gameplan related as Carson and Bush played their normal allotment. Feel free to keep Diabate on benches for Week 16.

Emmanwori stayed hot in Week 15, ripping off six solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. The rookie has been scintillating for fantasy managers and checks in as the DB1 in fppgsince Week 10. Already locked in as a top-10 IDP pick at his position in future seasons, start Emmanwori with confidence as a DB1 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against a suddenly banged-up Rams offense.

Antoine Winfield was excellent in Week 15, racking up eight solos and five assists. Winfield has posted two plus outings in his last three contests. Treat him as a top-15 option for a tasty Week 16 matchup against the Carolina Panthers. Count him as a top-10 option if Tykee Smith is sidelined again.

Derwin James was excellent in Week 15, posting two solos, eight assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Tap him as a top-five option despite the neutral-at-best on paper matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Battle was excellent in Week 15, ripping off seven solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Battle has now posted three straight plus outings, culminating with his first splash week since Week 1. Tap Battle as a DB2 option for Week 16, thanks to both his recent production and a tasty matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Jessie Bates showed up in Week 15, tallying six solos and two assists. Bates has been frustratingly inconsistent for fantasy managers this season, but remains a strong DB2 option for Week 16, albeit with a DB3 floor. Tap Bates as a top-20 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Gardner-Johnson showed up in Week15, tallying three solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and two passes defended. CJGJ has snared a pick in two straight contests, which has helped him provide two plus matchup for fantasy managers when they needed it most. Tap CJGJ as a DB2 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Mustapaha stayed hot out of the bye week, racking up six solos and four assists against the Tennessee Titans. Malik has tapped into his IDP potential and strung together three plus outings with at least five solos in each. The DB8in fppg over that stretch, feel free to tap Mustapha as a DB2 option for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts on Monday Night Football.

McKinney was excellent in Week 15, tallying seven solos, one assist, and three passes defended. Xavier is more bench depth than someone you want to start most weeks, but can be tapped as a flex2 option where needed for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Cam Bynum was excellent in Week 15, racking up seven solos and one assist. Bynum has turned it on over his last five contests, checking in as the DB10 in fppg since Week 10. Treat Cam as a top-25 option for Week 16, thanks to both his recent production and the plus matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Kam Lassiter was at it again in Week 15, tallying three solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Lassiter has heated up for IDP managers at the right time, registering three spike weeks in his last four contest
s, putting him back on the DB2/DB3 map. Treat him as such for a plus Week 16 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Marcus Jones showed up in Week 15, stacking eight solos and two assists. Jones carries a DB2 profile due to weekly DB1 upside and a DB4 floor.  Jones has had multiple splash weeks this season and has provided steady DB2 value despite the lower floor than normally associated with top-25 options. Fire Marus Jones up as a no-brainer top-25 option for a plus matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.
